Ploting 3D DEM Visualizations in Python¶

Introduction¶

One of the most awaited exercises is here! We have dealt with route analyses, image correction, choropleth maps, point maps, NDVI and others, but hardly have we ever touched on how to display any spatial object as a 3D surface. Isn't it exciting or are we the only ones who are fascinated with these genre of cartoons? Oh sorry, this is a GIS class. Ahem. When we think of 3D images in GIS, it looks like the gaming world has made inroads into ours and after luring us with their visuals, we harnessed it for our own needs. Starting with A. Sutherland who created the first 3D modeling software in the 1970s, 3D modeling has permeated to several industries from architecture to creating its own niche - 3D animation. 3D visualization in GIS is used in the following industries:

  • City planning
  • Building information modeling
  • Coastal modeling and analysis
  • Wind farm assessment

Here are some advantages of 3D Visualizations in GIS. Images is not everything when it comes to critically assessing its use..

  • They provide more detail by adding a z dimension to objects.
  • It depicts the scale of real-world objects based on explanatory illustrations

Terrain analysis is one of the most heavily used aspects of 3D visualization in GIS. Since you already know about Digital Elevation Models (DEMs), and you've seen a tad too many in 2D, how about if we visualize one in 3D?

First, as always, and forever will be, the requisite packages have to be called or else this exercise shall still remain a dreamy idea. We will work with Jupyter for the entirety of this exercise.

In [1]:

The mayavi package as commented above is responsible for 3D rendering. Now that we have the necessary packages, time to fish for the data. We shall extract our DEM from ASF Alaska website, and specifically the ALOS PALSAR dataset which is the highest resolution DEM we can get without paying a dime. We have discussed how to download the ALOS PALSAR dataset in another tutorial but for a refresh, this video explains everything succinctly. If you have followed the instructions from the video, look for the dataset with the ID AP_12103_FBD_F7180_RT1 and download it. It will come as a zipped file. If you are the lazy type (as some of us are prone to be at some point) you can access it from here.

Loading the DEM into python¶

In [2]:
# Go to path of ALOS PALSAR
path = "E:/documents/gis800_articles/jupyter/3D_dem"

Now that we have defined the path to the DEM, let's open it. Remember it came as a zipfile, so we will have to extract it first.

In [3]:
# loading the temp.zip and creating a zip object
with ZipFile (os.path.join(path, 'AP_12103_FBD_F7180_RT1.zip'), 'r') as zObject:
    # Extracting all the members of the zip into a specific location.
    zObject.extractall(path=os.path.join(path, 'DEM'))

If by now you can extract zipfiles in python without resorting to using specialized software, you are on your way to becoming a python wizard. well, almost.

For our DEM visualization exercise, we will only need the DEM. The os.listdir function will show us all the extracted files within our directory.

In [4]:

As mentioned earlier, we only need a DEM. Our file of interest is the one titled 'AP_12103_FBD_F7180_RT1.dem.tif'. Let's load it into Jupyter without further ado.

In [5]:
# Load it into jupyter
dem = os.path.join(path, 'DEM', 'AP_12103_FBD_F7180_RT1', 'AP_12103_FBD_F7180_RT1.dem.tif')

Although the DEM from the ASF Alaska website is good for our exercise, high resolution and perfect terrrain to stretch our 3D rendering capacity, it is too large for our computer's resources, and possibly yours too (pun intended). In other words, we want to clip it. The following section highlights the process of cropping a raster.

Cropping the DEM with a shapefile¶

Unlike the name (cropping) or how it's done in Qgis, cropping can be an awfully long process in python.

In [8]:
# The dreaded clipping exercise
from rasterio import mask # The tool to be used for the masking operation, from rasterio

Let's load the shapefile into our environment and extract it's geometries. The geometries are what shall make the clipping operation successful.

In [9]:
# Open the shapefile and extract geometries
with fiona.open("E:/documents/gis800_articles/jupyter/3D_dem/clipper.shp", 'r') as shapefile:
    shapes = [feature['geometry'] for feature in shapefile] # A list comprehension for loop think of it as
    # for feature in shapefile:
       ##return feature['geometry']

Now it's time to crop our raster. We shall use the mask function from rasterio.

In [12]:
# Open the raster and clip it using raster.mask
with rasterio.open(dem) as src:
    out_image, out_transform = rasterio.mask.mask(src, shapes, crop=True)
    out_meta = src.meta

After cropping, we get a new, albeit smaller in size raster but still retaining the metadata from the original larger raster. We are now left with one tiny exercise-- that is updating the metadata of our cropped raster.

In [13]:
# Update meta data for cropped raster
out_meta.update({'driver': "Gtiff",
                'height': out_image.shape[1],
                'width': out_image.shape[2],
                'transform': out_transform})

print(out_meta)

{'driver': 'Gtiff', 'dtype': 'int16', 'nodata': 0.0, 'width': 1884, 'height': 1480, 'count': 1, 'crs': CRS.from_epsg(32737), 'transform': Affine(12.5, 0.0, 302657.21875,
       0.0, -12.5, 9983459.25)}

Okay. Here is the thing: the new raster that we've created exists in our virtual environment but it's not saved somewhere in our computer. Although it is within our virtual environment (the Jupyter interface we are working on) it is far safer, better and smarter if it is also saved in your computer directory, just in case you or someone else wants to use it later on. We will first start by defining the path to where it shall be taken for safe keeping.

In [14]:
# Path to new clipped raster
clippedRaster = os.path.join(path, 'DEM', 'clippedRaster.tif') # This file is empty

The above code simply imputes the virtual raster into the empty file clippedRaster.tif. Think of it as writing a new story on a blank sheet of paper you had saved in your drawer (to keep it safe from the dog of course!).

In [15]:
# Write the clipped raster to the new path defined by clippedRaster variable above
with rasterio.open(clippedRaster, 'w', **out_meta) as dest:
    dest.write(out_image) # The image to be written to the clippedRaster variable/path

Plotting the Raster¶

Before we render our clipped raster as a 3D image, let's first of all view it in 2D. This will give us a glimpse of how it may possible be rendered in 3D.

Let's first load our clipped raster to our virtual environment.

In [16]:
# Open the clippedRaster file
demClipped = os.path.join(path, 'DEM', 'clippedRaster.tif')
demClipped = rasterio.open(demClipped)

Now let's display our clipped raster! Even if you have never been to this location depicted by the DEM, you can make a fair guess of what landform this is. Here is a clue: a natural tower.

In [17]:
# Display the clipped raster
from rasterio.plot import show
show(demClipped, cmap='terrain')

Plotting the DEM in 3D¶

Here comes the much awaited moment. It's time to plot our DEM in 3D using mayavi. All protocols observed, create a title of the mayavi image. Let's first define the title.

In [23]:
# Title for 3D Visualization
mlab.figure('DEM of Mt Kenya DEM')
Out[23]:
<mayavi.core.scene.Scene at 0x202ce9382c0>

Wait. Before you proceed, did you notice a small colorless and anonymous icon appear at the toolbar panel of your screen? That's mayavi called in for duty.

Now let's call the raster we want to be rendered as 3D. It is theclipped raster that we initially saved into our directory.

In [24]:
# Open the raster to visualize
with rasterio.open(os.path.join(path, 'DEM', 'clippedRaster.tif')) as src:
    elev = src.read(1)

Our raster has been loaded. Check. But mayavi works with numpy arrays. This means that it works with numerical values, which our raster holds, but our clipped raster is a .tif, not a numpy array. Luckily, because rasters are also composed of numerical values, we can extract these values, the x and y (for column and row) and the z value (for elevation).

To get the row column values, we will use the .shape() method which fetches the row column dimensions of a dataset(https://www.digitalocean.com/community/tutorials/python-shape-method).

In [25]:
nrows, ncols = elev.shape

The following code will create a rectangular grid of arrays, with evenly spaced values using np.arange(). The np.arange() will be responsible for creating the whole list of row column values for our matrix derived from our clipped raster.

The column values shall go to x. The row values shall go to y.

In [26]:
x, y = np.meshgrid(np.arange(ncols), np.arange(nrows))

In order for our 3D model to work, it not only needs the xy coordinate values, but also the height values, which were stored into the elev variable.

In [27]:
z = elev

The mlab.mesh function of mayavi package plots a surface using the x, y and z arrays we created above.

In [28]:
mesh = mlab.mesh(x, y, z)

Here is the ultimate finale: plotting the 3D visualization of our mountain.

Conclusion¶

3D visualizations are useful in depicting the scale of an image, as well as illustrating how a feature would look in real life. In matters DEM, colors, as shown after calling mesh.lab have been used to depict the various elevation regions. The 3D rendering of the mountain shows that the suface is a steep inclination from the top.
